The paper presents a general-purpose representation of semantically constrained graphs that can be applied to various fields, including chemistry, DNA, and quantum mechanics. The paper also highlights the applicability of the representation in machine learning, specifically in variational autoencoders. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), cs.CL (Computation and Language), cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition), and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
